Bad At RvR</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#c0c0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shadeazure@lighttanksofdaoc>shadeazure</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Initiate</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#000000>(5/9/03 5:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=113.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question: What do you think a 'Light Tank' should be lik</span><hr size=1> Light and heavy tanks should have the same basic personal defense capability when the effects of armor and evade are added together. Light tanks should be more reliant on evade, but armor+evade for all tanks should be identical in benefit in melee.<br>
<br>
Light and heavy tanks should have the same hit points.<br>
<br>
No tank should have to rely on reactional or positional styles. All tank classes should have effective versions of all kinds of styles available to them.<br>
<br>
Light tanks should have a constant non-sprint movement rate speed that is a little faster than normal. This benefit does not permit faster &quot;run song&quot; speed than normal.<br>
<br>
Heavy tanks should have an innate magic resistance superiority over the light tank. This makes up for the light tank's increased speed. While the light tank can close the distance to casters more quickly, the heavy tank can take more of their hits on the way there.<br>
<br>
Light tanks that max out weapon and dual wield lines should do more damage than polearm users that max out two weapon lines (armsman). This does not mean light tanks necessarily do more damage per attack, but over a short period of time (15 seconds or so), the light tank should have inflicted greater damage overall. Of course, heavy tanks that only specialize in one weapon line are even further behind in damage.<br>
<br>
Anything attacked by a heavy tank suffers from a melee attack speed penalty, causing reduced damage over time. In a duel between a heavy and a light tank, each with two weapon line specializations at equal level, the speed penalty inflicted by the heavy tank is exactly enough to offset the weapon damage superiority of the light tank so that over time, each inflicts about the same amount of damage on the other. If the heavy tank's target is attacking an ally instead of the tank, the speed penalty still applies, allowing a heavy tank to defend his friends. In addition, targets of a heavy tank's target do not count as being in melee, allowing them to cast spells without disruption. The attack speed decrease stacks with all other kinds of attack speed decreases, including the speed decreases caused by friendly heavy tanks.<br>
<br>
The light tank becomes a true offensive warrior with his speed and damage superiority. He is best when rushing at enemy casters and healers. The heavy tank, in contrast, is a defensive warrior that survives better against magic and protects allies while they cast spells. He is best when sticking near his own casters and attacking anyone who attacks them. The light tank will generally be able to kill non-tanks faster. The heavy tank ensures that casters are able to kill faster and gains kills through his allies. Both are equally capable when personally fighting other tanks.<br>
<br>
RvR is oriented toward attack more than defense, but the key is to maximize the offensive ability of the fighting group, not necessarily the individual. Healers, for example, do not add as much to offensive power as nukers do, but by keeping the nukers alive, they indirectly improve the group's offense. The heavy tank's defensive ability also indirectly improves group offense by protecting casters. Like nukers, light tanks will be directly adding to group offense.<br>
<br>
In PvE, a light and heavy tank can work in concert with the light tank dealing the heavy damage and probably drawing the aggro. The heavy tank also helps with damage, but more importantly, decreases the attack speed of the target so that the light tank takes less damage.<br>
<br>
Solo, a light tank will kill faster than a heavy tank in PvE due to better damage. The heavy tank should still win battles with the same amount of hit points remaining though, because the attack speed decrease he inflicts reduces the damage he takes. Downtime should be the same for each of the tanks. The light tank is still a better soloer and will level faster due to faster kills, and their ability to run faster to find prey, but the difference will not be that large. There are solo caster classes that are still far more powerful. In groups, both tanks are equally effective, and whether light or heavy, tanks ought to group rather than solo anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#ffffff><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=siryakk>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Journeyman</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#000000>(5/9/03 10:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=113.topic&index=4>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question: What do you think a 'Light Tank' should be lik</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The heavy tank's defensive ability also indirectly improves group offense by protecting casters. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Flaw:<br>
I have yet to see in your suggestion how the heavy tanks higher personal defence translates to any significantly better ability at protecting casters.<br>
<br>
The heavy tank could slow the attacks of one attacker, while the light tank would drop that attacker quicker.  The heavy tank would be roughly equally likely to kill the attacker before they killed the caster, but the light tank would get the attacker off the caster quicker than the heavy tank would.<br>
<br>
As far as I can tell, you want:<br>
Light tanks to have the same (mitigation+avoidance) and hps that heavy tanks have.<br>
Light tanks do more damage than heavy tanks.<br>
Light tanks run faster than heavy tanks.<br>
Heavy tanks have inherit magic resist.<br>
Heavy tanks have an inherit slow.<br>
<br>
Mate, that's not a very big set of differences between completely different classes.<br>
